This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Status hearing on November 7, 2022 at 01:15 pm.
On request of Atty. Carson, status rescheduled from 8:15 am to 1:15 pm.

No contact with: TN or CCJ. Defendant to avoid their residence and/or any location temporarily occupied by them. The defendant avoid contacting them or causing any person other than a party's attorney or law enforcement officer to contact them. Contact includes: contact at their home, work, school, public places, in person, by phone, in writing, by electronic communication or device, or in any other manner. Absolute sobriety.  No possession/consumption of any intoxicants. Not to possess or consume controlled substances or prescription medication w/out a valid prescription.

1:36 PM Defendant Tucker L Goeden appeared by video, in custody.  Prosecuting attorney Adam Yale Gerol in court for the State of Wisconsin. Statement by attorney Boaz on non-representation. Court advises of charges/penalties and finds probable cause. State recommends $2500 cash bail w/conditions. Court finds good cause to extend time limits for preliminary hearing.
Status hearing scheduled for November 7, 2022 at 08:15 am.
